The '''2009 Sony Ericsson Open''' (also known as '''2009 Miami Masters''') was a men's and women's [[tennis]] tournament held from March 23 to April 5, 2009. It was the 25th edition of the [[Miami Masters]] event and was played on outdoor [[Tennis court#Hard courts|hard courts]] at the [[Tennis Center at Crandon Park]] in [[Key Biscayne, Florida]], located near [[Miami]]. The tournament was part of [[2009 ATP World Tour]] and [[2009 WTA Tour]], classified as [[ATP World Tour Masters 1000]] and [[WTA Premier tournaments|Premier Mandatory]] event respectively.

The men's singles event was won by British player [[Andy Murray]], who defeated [[Novak Djokovic]] in the final. [[Victoria Azarenka]] of [[Belarus]] won the women's singles event by defeating defending champion [[Serena Williams]]. Both Murray and Azarenka were first-time winners at the tournament and also the first to win from their respective countries. In the doubles events, [[Max Mirnyi]] and [[Andy Ram]] won the men's title by defeating the team of [[Ashley Fisher]] and [[Stephen Huss (tennis)|Stephen Huss]]. The women's doubles title was won by [[Svetlana Kuznetsova]] and [[Amelie Mauresmo]] who overcame [[Kveta Peschke]] and [[Lisa Raymond]] in the final match.

==Tournament==
The 2009 Sony Ericsson Open was the 25th edition of the [[Miami Masters]] tournament and was held at [[Tennis Center at Crandon Park]], [[Key Biscayne, Florida|Key Biscayne]] near [[Miami]], Florida.<ref name="review">{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonopen.com/1/en/news/newsarticle_2942.asp|title=Another Banner Year For The Sony Ericsson Open|publisher=Sony Ericsson Open|accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref> The tournament was a joint event between the [[Association of Tennis Professionals]] (ATP) and the [[Women's Tennis Association]] (WTA) and was part of the [[2009 ATP World Tour]] and the [[2009 WTA Tour]] calendars. The tournament consisted of both men's and women's singles and doubles events which were played on 12 Laykold Cushion Plus [[hard court]]s.<ref name="Facts">{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonopen.com/3/en/media/t_facts.asp|title=2009 Sony Ericsson Open: Tourney Info: Fact Sheet|publisher=Sony Ericsson Open|accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref> The total prize money for the tournament was US$9,000,000 with $4,500,000 assigned equally to ATP and WTA events. Singles winners received $605,500 each and doubles winning teams received $225,000 each.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonopen.com/3/en/seo/prize_mo.asp|title=Prize Money|publisher=Sony Ericsson Open|accessdate=2009-05-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/tennis/1/en/tournaments/profile/403.asp|title=Tennis <U+2013> ATP World Tour <U+2013> Tournaments - Sony Ericsson Open|work=ATP World Tour|publisher=ATP Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-05-18}}</ref>

The tournament was conducted from March 23 to April 5, with qualifying draws played on March 23<U+2013>24 and main draws from March 25 to April 5. Both the men's and women's singles draws consisted of 96 players and the doubles draws consisted of 32 teams.<ref name="Facts" /> The qualifying draw consisted of 43 men and 42 women who competed for 12 positions each in the men's and women's final draw.<ref name="qfield">{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonopen.com/1/en/news/newsarticle_2523.asp|title=Sony Ericsson Open Announces Qualifying Field|publisher=Sony Ericsson Open|accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonopen.com/1/en/news/newsarticle_2150.asp|title=2009 Sony Ericsson Open Player Fields Announced|publisher=Sony Ericsson Open|language=singles fields|accessdate=2009-05-17}}</ref>

==Players==
47 of the top 50 players in the [[ATP rankings]] entered the men's singles event at the tournament<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonopen.com/3/en/players/default.asp|title=2009 Sony Ericsson Open: Players|publisher=[[Sony Ericsson|Sony Ericsson Open]]|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> with [[Rafael Nadal]] [[Glossary of tennis#S|seeded first]], followed by [[Roger Federer]], [[Novak Djokovic]] and [[Andy Murray]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonopen.com/3/en/assets/pdfs/draws/09ATP_MDS13.pdf|title=Sony Ericsson Open-Men Draw Singles|publisher=Sony Ericsson Open|accessdate=2009-05-17}}</ref>  Defending champion [[Nikolay Davydenko]] withdrew ahead of the tournament due to a foot injury.<ref name="withdrawals">{{cite news|url=http://msn.foxsports.com/tennis/story/9359772/Sharapova-withdraws-from-Sony-Ericsson-Open|title=Sharapova withdraws from Sony Ericsson|date=2009-03-20|work=[[Fox Sports]]|publisher=[[MSN]]|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> [[Richard Gasquet]], who was initially going to play, withdrew prior to his first match after suffering from right shoulder injury. Gasquet was replaced by [[Glossary of tennis#L|lucky loser]] [[Bjorn Phau]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lequipe.fr/Tennis/20090328_175651_gasquet-renonce.html|title=Tennis - ATP - Miami - Gasquet renonce|date=2009-03-28|publisher=L'Equipe|language=French|accessdate=2009-05-17}}</ref><ref name = "Saturday>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/News/Tennis/2009/03/miamisaturday.aspx|title=Nadal Leads Spanish Foursome Along With Murray Into Third Round|date=2009-03-28|work=atpworldtour.com|publisher=Association of Tennis Professionals|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref> 12 players progressed from the qualifying draws to the main draw<ref name="quali results">{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonopen.com/1/en/news/newsarticle_2782.asp|title=Americans Dent, Craybas Qualify Into Main Draw|publisher=Sony Ericsson Open|accessdate=2009-05-17}}</ref> and six players, including [[Lleyton Hewitt]] and [[Marcos Baghdatis]], were given [[Glossary of tennis#W|wildcard]] entries.<ref name="wildcards">{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonopen.com/1/en/news/newsarticle_2613.asp|title=Sony Ericsson Open Announces Wildcards|publisher=Sony Ericsson Open|accessdate=2009-05-17}}</ref>

In the women's singles field, defending champion [[Serena Williams]] was top seeded, with number two [[Dinara Safina]] only 311 points behind her in the [[WTA rankings]] at the start of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12781~1678415,00.html|title=Serena Seeks Sixth Miami Title as Dinara Threatens|date=2009-03-24|work=Sony Ericssson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref> [[Maria Sharapova]] was expected to return to singles tennis at this tournament after playing doubles matches in the previous tournament, the [[2009 BNP Paribas Open]]. Sharapova, who had not played singles matches since August 2008, withdrew due to a continued lack of fitness.<ref name="withdrawals" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tennis/7958398.stm|title=Sharapova puts off singles return|date=2009-03-22|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-18}}</ref> [[Jelena Dokic]], [[Sania Mirza]] and [[Alexa Glatch]] were among the eight players who received wildcard entries.<ref name="wildcards" /> 12 players progressed from qualifying draws to main draw.<ref name="quali results" />

The doubles draws were led by defending champions [[Bob Bryan|Bob]] and [[Mike Bryan]] on the men's side and [[Cara Black]] and [[Liezel Huber]] on the women's side. [[Katarina Srebotnik]], one of the women's doubles defending champions, had not recovered from an injury picked up in December 2008 and did not participate. Her partner from the previous year, [[Ai Sugiyama]] partnered with Russian [[Daniela Hantuchova]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonopen.com/1/en/news/newsarticle_2519.asp|title=2009 Sony Ericsson Open Doubles Player Field Announced|publisher=Sony Ericsson Open|accessdate=2009-05-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/DoublesNewsDetail/0,,12781~1658138,00.html|title=Black, Huber Look to Rebound in Miami|date=2009-03-25|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref> [[Marina Erakovic]] <U+2013> [[Tiantian Sun]] and [[Francesca Schiavone]] <U+2013> [[Chan Yung-jan]] withdrew from the tournament due to respective injuries to Erakovic and Chan.<ref name="WTA doubles1">{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/DoublesNewsDetail/0,,12781~1658141,00.html|title=Most Seeds Reign Supreme in Miami Doubles|date=2009-03-30|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref> The doubles draws included five wildcard entries in total.

==Events==
===Men's singles===
[[File:Djokovic Miami 2009 1.jpg|right|thumb|[[Novak Djokovic]] was the runner-up at the tournament.]]
{{main|2009 Sony Ericsson Open - Men's Singles}}

All the seeded players received a [[Glossary of tennis#B|bye]] into the second round. Wildcards [[Marcos Baghdatis]] and [[Lleyton Hewitt]] were among the players progressing into the second round, while Germans [[Philipp Kohlschreiber]] and former World no. 2 [[Tommy Haas]] were the major upsets.<ref name="Day1BBC">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/7964465.stm|title=Keothavong makes early Miami exit|date=2009-03-25|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref> Most seeded players continued their progress into the third round with eighth seed [[Fernando Verdasco]] winning his 200th ATP tour match in his career. [[Ivo Karlovic]] and [[David Nalbandian]] were among the seeded players defeated in second round. Lucky loser [[Bjorn Phau]] was promoted into the third round after his opponent [[Albert Montanes]] suffered a hamstring injury during the second set of the match and was forced to withdraw.<ref name = "Saturday">{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/News/Tennis/2009/03/miamifriday.aspx|title=Federer Cruises; Dent Saves Match Point|date=2009-03-27|work=ATP World Tour|publisher=ATP Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-05-19}}</ref><ref name="Day3BBC">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/7969332.stm|title=Federer overpowers qualifier Kim|date=2009-03-28|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref> Frenchman [[Ga<U+00EB>l Monfils]] took a hard-fought win over 22nd seed and former world number 1 [[Marat Safin]] in a third round match played for nearly three hours. Qualifier [[Taylor Dent]] continued his successful run by defeating [[Tommy Robredo]] in the third round. [[Tomas Berdych]] and [[Radek Stepanek]] overcame higher seeded players [[James Blake]] and [[Fernando Gonzalez]] en route to the fourth round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/News/Tennis/2009/03/miamimonday2.aspx|title=Nadal, Del Potro, Troicki advance to Fourth Round in straight sets|date=2009-03-30|work=atpworldtour.com|publisher=[[Association of Tennis Professionals]]|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/News/Tennis/2009/03/miamisunday1.aspx|title=Roddick Passes Tursunov Test; Monfils Saves 2 M.P.|date=2009-03-29|work=atpworldtour.com|publisher=Association of Tennis Professionals |accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref><ref name="Day5BBC">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/7971049.stm|title=Safina & Ivanovic in shock exits |date=2009-03-29|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref>

Top seed [[Rafael Nadal]] faced an uphill battle against [[Stanislas Wawrinka]] in the fourth round match, facing a [[Glossary of tennis#T|tiebreak]] in each set, eventually defeating him 7<U+2013>6(2), 7<U+2013>6(4). Second seed [[Roger Federer]] defeated Dent in the fourth round to set up a quarterfinal match with long time rival [[Andy Roddick]], who overcame [[Ga<U+00EB>l Monfils]] in a two-set match. [[Novak Djokovic]], [[Andy Murray]], [[Juan Martin del Potro]], Verdasco and [[Jo-Wilfried Tsonga]] made it into the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/News/Tennis/2009/03/miamituesday1.aspx|title=Nadal Battles Past Wawrinka; Murray Looks For Vengeance|date=2009-03-31|work=atpworldtour.com|publisher=Association of Tennis Professionals|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/News/Tennis/2009/03/miamituesday2.aspx|title=Federer, Roddick Ready For Miami Rematch|date=2009-03-31|work=atpworldtour.com|publisher=Association of Tennis Professionals|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref><ref name="Day7BBC">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/7975475.stm|title=Murray eases into Miami quarters|date=2009-04-01|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref> Del Potro defeated Nadal in the three-set quarterfinal match to reach the first [[ATP World Tour Masters 1000|ATP Masters]] semifinal of his career. Del Potro took the final set 7<U+2013>6(3) on a tiebreak after losing the second set. Murray faced Verdasco in the second quarterfinal in a rematch of [[2009 Australian Open]] fourth round. Verdasco suffered an injury in the second game of the match and had to be seen by his [[physiotherapist|physio]]. He was not in good enough shape to compete with Murray and eventually lost 1<U+2013>6, 2<U+2013>6.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/News/Tennis/2009/03/miamithursday2.aspx|title=Del Potro Digs Deep To Derail Nadal; Murray Eases Into SFs|date=2009-04-02|work=ATP World Tour|publisher=ATP Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-05-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/7978965.stm|title=Murray marches on but Nadal loses |date=2009-04-03|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref> Federer defeated Roddick 6<U+2013>3, 4<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>4 while Djokovic moved past Tsonga 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>4 to advance to the semifinals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/News/Tennis/2009/03/miamiwednesday2.aspx|title=Federer Edges Past Roddick; Djokovic Solves Tsonga Riddle|date=2009-04-01|work=atpworldtour.com|publisher=Association of Tennis Professionals|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/7978060.stm|title=Federer edges to win over Roddick |date=2009-04-02|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref> Djokovic rallied back to defeat Federer in the first semifinal after losing the first set 3<U+2013>6. The third seed however kept his consistency in the next two sets and won them 6<U+2013>2, 6<U+2013>3.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mark |last=Hodgkinson |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/rogerfederer/5102256/Roger-Federer-loses-his-cool-in-semi-final-defeat-by-Novak-Djokovic.html|title=Roger Federer loses his cool in semi-final defeat to Novak Djokovic|date=2009-04-03|work=Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Publishing Group|accessdate=2009-05-19}}</ref> Murray edged past del Potro 6<U+2013>1, 5<U+2013>7, 6<U+2013>2 in the second semifinal to enter his second straight Masters final. Murray faltered in the second set of the match conceding two service breaks. However he recovered in the final set, gaining an early break of serve, to win the match.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mark |last=Hodgkinson|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/andymurray/5104356/Andy-Murray-to-face-Novak-Djokovic-in-Miami-Masters-final.html|title=Andy Murray to face Novak Djokovic in Miami Masters final|date=2009-04-03|work=Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Publishing Group|accessdate=2009-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/7982365.stm|title=Brilliant Murray into Miami final |last=Newbery|first=Piers|date=2009-04-04|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref>

Djokovic and Murray appeared in their seventh and fourth Masters final and 19th and 17th career finals repectively. Djokovic led the head-to-head tally against Murray, but Murray had won the last two encounters between them. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/tennis/livematch/277096.html|title=Miami Masters - Final - Men |date=2009-04-05|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]/[[Eurosport]]|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> In the match, Murray dominated the first set moving into an early 4<U+2013>0 lead. Djokovic improved his serve from that point but lost the set 6<U+2013>2. A role reversal in the second set saw Djokovic move into a 4-1 lead. Murray fought back, however, to level the score to 5<U+2013>5 and ultimately won the set 7<U+2013>5 to secure the victory. This was Murray's third title win of the season and eleventh of his career. It was also his third Masters win of the career. Murray credited his improved fitness for his win. Djokovic, who had struggled with excessive heat in the past, struggled once again to assimilate with the temperature. He admitted that he was impatient early in the match, which resulted in him making too many [[Glossary of tennis#U|unforced errors]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/7983446.stm|title=Murray wins Miami Masters title|last=Newbery|first=Piers|date=2009-04-05|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref>

;Final score
{{flagicon|GBR}} '''[[Andy Murray]]''' def. {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Novak Djokovic]], 6<U+2013>2, 7<U+2013>5.

===Women's singles===
[[File:Azarenka Miami 2009 1.jpg|thumb|right|[[Victoria Azarenka]] won third title of her career.]]
{{main|2009 Sony Ericsson Open - Women's Singles}}

All the seeded players received a bye into the second round. Seven seeded players were ousted from the second round including third seed [[Jelena Jankovic]], who was defeated by [[Gisela Dulko]], and eighth seed [[Marion Bartoli]], who lost to qualifier [[Anastasiya Yakimova]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12781~1651645,00.html|title=Mauresmo Joins Winning Seeds in Miami|date=2009-03-27|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12781~1651689,00.html|title=Dulko Stuns Jankovic in Miami Opener|date=2009-03-28|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref><ref name="Day4BBC">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/7962505.stm|title=Murray battles through in Miami|date=2009-03-28|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref> Second seed [[Dinara Safina]], [[Vera Zvonareva]] and [[Ana Ivanovic]] were among the nine seeded players who were eliminated in the third round.<ref name="Day5BBC" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12781~1651695,00.html|title=Inspired Stosur Ousts Safina From Miami|date=2009-03-29|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref> Three times former champion and fifth seed [[Venus Williams]] faced stiff competition from [[Agnieszka Radwanska]] in fourth round. Williams lost the first set but prevailed in later sets to win the match. [[Li Na (tennis)|Li Na]] and [[Ekaterina Makarova]] also fought hard for a place in the quarterfinals, with Li coming out strong in the three set match, winning 7<U+2013>6(3), 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12781~1651702,00.html|title=Miami Quarters Take Shape|date=2009-03-30|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref>

[[Svetlana Kuznetsova]] beat [[Caroline Wozniacki]] in the first of the quarterfinals. Kuznetsova looked good to win the match in straight sets after building a 6<U+2013>4, 5<U+2013>2 lead, however Wozniacki fought back to win the second set on a tiebreak. Kuznetsova ultimately won 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>7(5), 6<U+2013>1. [[Victoria Azarenka]] defeated [[Samantha Stosur]] 6<U+2013>1, 6<U+2013>0 in the second quarterfinal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12781~1651720,00.html|title=Svetlana Storms Into Miami Semis|date=2009-03-31|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref><ref name="Day7BBC" /> Williams sisters [[Serena Williams|Serena]] and Venus set up the second semifinal after defeating Li Na and [[Iveta Benesova]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12781~1651722,00.html|title=Venus, Serena Set Up Miami SF Date|date=2009-04-01|work=Sony Ericssson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/7977914.stm|title=Williams sisters to meet in semis |date=2009-04-02|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref> The Williams sisters had met 19 times before their semifinal meeting, Venus leading the [[Williams Sisters rivalry|head-to-head]] tally 10<U+2013>9. Serena won this time, scoring 6<U+2013>4, 3<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3 in a closely fought match. Azarenka came on top in the second semifinal defeating Kuznetsova 6<U+2013>3, 2<U+2013>6, 5<U+2013>7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12781~1651727,00.html|title=Azarenka, Serena To Meet In Miami Final|date=2009-04-02|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/7980425.stm|title=Serena beats Venus to reach final|date=2009-04-03|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref>

Serena and Azarenka met in their careers' 46th and seventh career finals respectively, with Serena appearing in her third consecutive final at the event, having won on the last two occasions. Azarenka dominated the final match, as Serena was playing while nursing a leg injury. Azarenka won the match 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>1, securing third title of her career. Azarenka stated that she was very nervous in the final [[Glossary of tennis#G|game]] of the match and described her win as the "the biggest moment in [her] career". Serena mentioned that it was difficult for her to move to the left, but she still played with maximum effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12781~1673234,00.html|title=A Star Is Born: Azarenka Wins in Miami|date=2009-04-04|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/7983547.stm|title=Azarenka sees off Serena in final|last=Newbery|first=Piers|date=2009-04-04|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref>

;Final score
{{flagicon|BLR}} '''[[Victoria Azarenka]]''' def. {{flagicon|USA}} [[Serena Williams]], 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>1.

===Men's doubles===
{{main|2009 Sony Ericsson Open - Men's Doubles}}

Four seeded teams were eliminated in the first round of the event. [[Daniel Nestor]] <U+2013> [[Nenad Zimonjic]] were the highest ranked team to lose, falling to [[Nicolas Almagro]] <U+2013> [[David Ferrer]], along with third seeds [[Mahesh Bhupathi]] <U+2013> [[Mark Knowles]], who lost to French duo [[Julien Benneteau]] <U+2013> [[Jo-Wilfried Tsonga]]. Bennetau <U+2013> Tsonga continued their progress into the third round defeating [[Rik de Voest]] <U+2013> [[Bobby Reynolds]]. They were joined by [[Julian Knowle]] <U+2013> [[Jurgen Melzer]] who triumphed over Almagro <U+2013> Ferrer. Only two seeded teams, [[Bob Bryan]] <U+2013> [[Mike Bryan]] and [[Bruno Soares]] <U+2013> [[Kevin Ullyett]], made it into the quarterfinals and faced each other in the round. The Bryan brothers, who were the defending champions, overcame Soares <U+2013> Ullyett in a two-set match. [[Ashley Fisher]] <U+2013> [[Stephen Huss (tennis)|Stephen Huss]], Knowle <U+2013> Melzer and [[Max Mirnyi]] <U+2013> [[Andy Ram]] were the other teams who made it into the semifinals.

The Bryan brothers faced Fisher <U+2013> Huss in the first semifinal and lost 7<U+2013>6(6), 6<U+2013>4 ending their streak of winning 13 consecutive matches. Mirnyi <U+2013> Ram encountered much harder competition against Knowle <U+2013> Melzer and saved five [[Glossary of tennis#M|match points]] before winning 4<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>6(8), [10<U+2013>8]. In the final, there were no service breaks in the first set with Fisher <U+2014> Huss winning it in the tiebreak 7<U+2013>4. Mirnyi <U+2013> Ram came back strongly winning the second set. The match-tiebreak decided the outcome of the final, with Mirnyi <U+2013> Ram winning the tiebreak and match 6<U+2013>7(4), 6<U+2013>2, [10<U+2013>7]. It was Mirnyi's 36th and Ram's 16th men's doubles title of the career and their second title as a team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atpworldtour.atponline.net/tennis/1/en/news/newsarticle_2927.asp|title=Mirnyi-Ram Rally To Capture Sony Ericsson Open Doubles Title|work=ATP World Tour|publisher=ATP Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-05-21}}</ref>

;Final score
{{flagicon|BLR}} '''[[Max Mirnyi]]''' / {{flagicon|ISR}} '''[[Andy Ram]]''' def. {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ashley Fisher]] / {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Stephen Huss (tennis)|Stephen Huss]], 6<U+2013>7(4), 6<U+2013>2, [10<U+2013>7].

===Women's doubles===
[[File:Kuznetsova Miami 2009 1.jpg|thumb|right|[[Svetlana Kuznetsova]], along with [[Amelie Mauresmo]] won the women's doubles event.]]
{{main|2009 Sony Ericsson Open - Women's Doubles}}

[[Daniela Hantuchova]] <U+2013> [[Ai Sugiyama]], who lost to wildcard entrants [[Petra Martic]] <U+2013> [[Coco Vandeweghe]], were the only seeded pair to drop out in the first round.<ref name="WTA doubles1" /> Another wildcarded team [[Svetlana Kuznetsova]] <U+2013> [[Amelie Mauresmo]] defeated the top seeds [[Cara Black]] <U+2013> [[Liezel Huber]] in the second round. Eighth seeds [[Maria Kirilenko]] <U+2013> [[Flavia Pennetta]] were also eliminated in second round, losing to [[Chuang Chia-jung]] <U+2013> [[Sania Mirza]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/DoublesNewsDetail/0,,12781~1658160,00.html|title=Kuznetsova, Mauresmo Pull Off Upset in Miami|date=2009-03-31|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref> Chuang <U+2013> Mirza continued their march into the semifinal defeating second seeds [[Anabel Medina Garrigues]] <U+2013> [[Virginia Ruano Pascual]] 6<U+2013>3, 7<U+2013>6(4). They were joined by Kuznetsova <U+2013> Mauresmo, [[Anna-Lena Groenefeld]] <U+2013> [[Patty Schnyder]] and [[Kveta Peschke]] <U+2013> [[Lisa Raymond]], the only seeded team left in the draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/DoublesNewsDetail/0,,12781~1658166,00.html|title=Three Seeded Teams Eliminated in Miami|date=2009-04-01|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref>

Kuznetsova <U+2013> Mauresmo defeated Groenefeld <U+2013> Schnyder 7<U+2013>6(6), 6<U+2013>3 to enter their third final as a team. Peschke <U+2013> Raymond overcame Chuang <U+2013> Mirza 7<U+2013>6(5), 6<U+2013>4 to secure the second spot in the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/DoublesNewsDetail/0,,12781~1658176,00.html|title=Kuznetsova, Mauresmo Make Miami Final|date=2009-04-03|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref> Kuznetsova <U+2013> Mauresmo continued their winning spree in the final, defeating Peschke <U+2013> Raymond 4<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3, [10<U+2013>3]. The title was Kuznetsova's 14th, Mauresmo's third and their second as a team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/page/DoublesNewsDetail/0,,12781~1658184,00.html|title=Kuznetsova, Mauresmo Surprise Winners in Miami|date=2009-04-06|work=Sony Ericsson WTA Tour|publisher=WTA Tour Inc.|accessdate=2009-06-01}}</ref>

;Final score
{{flagicon|RUS}} '''[[Svetlana Kuznetsova]]''' / {{flagicon|FRA}} '''[[Amelie Mauresmo]]''' def. {{flagicon|CZE}} [[Kveta Peschke]] / {{flagicon|USA}} [[Lisa Raymond]], 4<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3, [10<U+2013>3].

==Viewership==
===Broadcasting===
The tournament was broadcast on television channels worlwide. The British television station [[Sky Sports]] held rights to broadcast the tournament from the first round through to the final. Both the men's and women's finals were shown on [[CBS]] in the United States. The tournament also had around 44 hours of live coverage in the United States. The tournament was broadcast for more than 2000 hours and seen by over 153 million people worldwide.<ref>{{cite web  |url=http://www.sonyericssonopen.com/1/en/news/newsarticle_2431.asp|title=Two domestic networks to broadcast 37 hours of live tennis coverage |work=sonyericssonopen.com |publisher=[[Sony Ericsson]] |accessdate=28 July 2009}}</ref><ref name = "Broadcasting">{{cite web  |url=http://www.sonyericssonopen.com/1/en/news/newsarticle_2942.asp|title=Another banner year for the Sony Ericsson Open |work=sonyericssonopen.com |publisher=[[Sony Ericsson]] |accessdate=28 July 2009}}</ref> 
===Attendance===
According to the event organisers, 293,228 people attended the 22 sessions across the 12 days of the tournament.<ref name = "Broadcasting" /> This was the second highest attendance in the tournament's history and four sessions were sellouts.

